from sklearn.metrics import calinski_harabasz_score
from sklearn.metrics import davies_bouldin_score

def elbow_method(X, model_name, k_max):
    scores = []
    for k in range(1, k_max+1):
        model = model_name(n_clusters=k)
        model.fit(X)
        wcss = model_name.score(X) * -1
        scores.append(wcss)
    return scores

def count_clustering_scores(X, cluster_num, model_name, score_fun):
    if isinstance(cluster_num, int):
        cluster_num_iter = [cluster_num]
    else:
        cluster_num_iter = cluster_num
        
    scores = []    
    for k in cluster_num_iter:
        model_instance = model_name(n_clusters=k)
        labels = model_instance.fit_predict(X)
        wcss = score_fun(X, labels)
        scores.append(wcss)
    
    if isinstance(cluster_num, int):
        return scores[0]
    else:
        return scores
    
def celinskiego_harabasz_index(data, model_name, k_max):
    scores = []
    for k in range(2, k_max+1):
        model = model_name(n_clusters = k)
        labels = model.fit_predict(data)
        scores.append(calinski_harabasz_score(data, labels))
        
    return scores
    
def davies_bouldina_index(data, model_name, k_max):
    scores = []
    for k in range(2, k_max+1):
        model = model_name(n_clusters = k)
        labels = model.fit_predict(data)
        scores.append(davies_bouldin_score(data, labels))  
    
    return scores

def plot_scores(scores):
    x_ticks = list(range(1, len(scores) + 1))
    plt.plot(x_ticks, scores, 'bx-')
    plt.xlabel('k')
    plt.ylabel('Within-cluster sum of squares')
    plt.show()
    
def plot_3d(data, model_name, k_max):
    for k in range(2, k_max+1):
        if model_name == KMeans:
            model = model_name(n_clusters = k)
            labels = model.fit_predict(data)
            out = model.predict(data)
        if model_name == AgglomerativeClustering:
            agglomerative = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k)
            out = agglomerative.fit_predict(data)
            
        if model_name == GaussianMixture:
            agglomerative = GaussianMixture(n_clusters=k)
            out = agglomerative.fit_predict(data)           
            
        
        fig = plt.figure()
        ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
        ax.scatter3D(data['X1'], data['X2'], data['X3'], c = out)
        ax.set_title('KMeans clustering: ' + str(k) + " clusters")
        ax.set_xlabel('x')
        ax.set_ylabel('y')
        ax.set_zlabel('z')
        
        ax.view_init(70, -40)
        
def plot_k(data, model_name, k):
    
    if model_name == KMeans:
        model = model_name(n_clusters = k)
        labels = model.fit_predict(data)
        out = model.predict(data)
    if model_name == AgglomerativeClustering:
        agglomerative = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k)
        out = agglomerative.fit_predict(data)
            
        
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
    ax.scatter3D(data['X1'], data['X2'], data['X3'], c = out)
    ax.set_title('KMeans clustering: ' + str(k) + " clusters")
    ax.set_xlabel('x')
    ax.set_ylabel('y')
    ax.set_zlabel('z')
        
    ax.view_init(70, -40)

Clustering score - description¶

Elbow score¶

A fundamental step for any unsupervised algorithm is to determine the optimal number of clusters into which the data may be clustered. The Elbow Method is one of the most popular methods to determine this optimal value of k.

Silhouette score¶

The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette ranges from 1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate. If many points have a low or negative value, then the clustering configuration may have too many or too few clusters.

lower (near 0) - better¶

Celinskiego-Harabasza Index¶

It is also known as the Variance Ratio Criterion.

The score is defined as ratio between the within-cluster dispersion and the between-cluster dispersion.

higher value - better¶

Daviesa-Bouldina Index¶

The score is defined as the average similarity measure of each cluster with its most similar cluster, where similarity is the ratio of within-cluster distances to between-cluster distances. Thus, clusters which are farther apart and less dispersed will result in a better score.

The minimum score is zero, with lower values indicating better clustering.

lower value - better¶

Conclusions¶

I have tried four metrics for clustering. These metrics give different results. The worst for me was Celinski-Harabasz index and the best is Silhouette method or Davies-Bouldin index.

In my opinion (and the metrics) the best number of clusters is four.
